title: For Sale:  British Enfield No. 4 Mk. 1 Rifle (1944) w/ Extras
postcontent: No. 4 Mk. 1 .303 Enfield Rifle. This was made in Maltby with a 1944 date. The receiver is marked as No.4 Mk. I* but, according to Ian Skennerton's book, some Maltby rifles were mistakenly marked with an *. This was rebuilt at Fazakerly in 1947 and it looks like it was destined to be converted to a Mk. 2 as there is a screw on the right sight which was something that was done in the conversion program. The bore is excellent with no pitting or darkness, this has a brass butt plate and the sling has steel ends. All numbers, including the magazine and the fore stock match, except the bolt which for some reason has a "U.S." on it. Also included is a new old stock pull-through, a wire gauze, a plastic Mk.V Oiler, 5 Charger Clips and a No. 4 Bayonet, but there is no scabbard. The wood has the usual dents & dings and the butt stock has a rack number "2" on it. There are NO Import Marks. This is a very nice piece and I am selling it as I have 9 other Enfield rifles and my gun safe does not have expandable sides.

title: For Sale:  Astra "Firecat" .25 ACP Pocket Pistol
postcontent:
The Astra Firecat is a semi-auto .25 caliber pocket pistol, made in Spain between the years 1920-1968. It’s a high-quality, Browning-designed pistol that has a grip safety, magazine safety and a manual safety. During WWII many German Officers carried these guns as a private purchase backup gun to their issue sidearm, and many of these guns were brought back by returning GI’s. The pistol has a blue finish and brown plastic factory grips with the Astra logo, and the word “FIRECAT” at the bottom of the grips. The pistol is in very good condition. Includes 1 factory magazine, cleaning rod and original box.

title: For Sale:  M-11 9mm Semi/Full Auto Double Threaded Barrel
postcontent:
If you want the versatility of a standard 3/4x10 9mm thread and also want a 1/2x28 thread, then this is the barrel for you!!!!

The barrel is super easy to install. My first one I put on took m about 12-15 mins' but on my last MAC it took 4 mins to change the barrel. Its just a super well built easy to work with and has all the treads you'd ever need to have. I have them on all my MACs and M-11's. I just order one too many this last order, my fault will end up your win!

This barrel is very cool because it allows you to have multiple threads on just 1 high quality made barrel. I have them on all my MG MAC and the first one i installed is still on and probably close to 24-28k rounds through it and still as accurate and has not faded any since the day it was installed. That's why I have them on all 6 of my SMG's .

For the barrel being sold, I opened the package to make sure it was perfect in aesthetics and to check the thread quality. At this time i felt the threads and they are very smooth with no rough marks. I tested the 1/2x28 threads with my AAC Ti-Rant 9 and it fit perfectly and snug on the 1/2x28 threads. I then checked my Bowers Group CAC Suppressor on the barrels other threads, the 3/4x10 threads and they fit tight and smooth as well. It truly is one of the best threaded barrels I own. I can honestly its just as good if not better that some of my several hundred dollar Jarvis Barrels I use on my high end pistols. If I'd had known about these sooner, I have no doubt I'd have them on more pistols.

It truly is a GREAT GREAT DEAL !

The 1/2x28 threads are standard on .22 as well as on a standard 9mm barrel so you can thread on suppressors and muzzle brakes. The other thread ¾ X 10 is the standard thread for the M10/9 and M11/9 which will also fit any sub gun silencer like Gemtechs Viper or Bowers CAC, just to name a few. This Barrel Fits any MAC, M/10, M-11 SMG, Semi Auto and MPA mid sized 9mm.

title: For Sale:  Hakim 8mm rifle
postcontent:
For sale is an Egyptian Hakim Rifle. This is an unusual operating system and it is quite unique.  This rifle has had the stock refinished as well as the finish on the rifle with a non glare coating which makes it rust resistant and very attractive.  The history behind this rifle comes from Sweden.  Originally the Swedish produced the AG42, which was a gas operated semi automatic rifle which operated very similar to the American Garand.  After the end of WW2 the Swedish sold their tools and equipment to the Egyptians as well as assisted them in setting up their factory to produce the Swedish Rifle now known as the Hakim.  

This Hakim is a good shooter and will come with a reproduction operators manual and a bayonet, which is a very pricey and hard item to find.  Also included is the gas adjustment tool which is necessary to change the level on the gas port depending on what ammunition you use.  The box magazine is removable and holds a total of ten rounds.  The rifle includes a sling and uses 8 mm Mauser ammunition.  When loading the rifle you can use the stripper clips that come with mauser surplus ammo to load the gun.  All in all this is a very unusual gun and a good shooter.  This rifle is in very good condition and a blast to shoot.  Feel free to ask any questions by contacting me by email.
